The Breitling Reserve de Marche B14047, part of the Windrider collection, is an interesting and rare model, with a history linked to the relaunch and expansion of the Breitling in the 90s. Here is its history and context:

Historical context - Breitling in the 90s

After a difficult period during the quartz crisis (70s-80s), Breitling was relaunched by Ernest Schneider, who bought the brand in 1979. During the 90s, Breitling focused on returning to the mechanical movement and to the historical identity of the house as a manufacturer of professional, pilot and instrument watches.

In this context, the Windrider collection was born, designed to combine sportiness and luxury, characterized by:

Gentlemen's ring (as on the Chronomat)

Shiny steels

Elegant yet solid design

Two-tone versions with solid 18 kt gold inserts (not plated)

Birth of the B14047 – Reserve de Marche

The B14047 is one of the few Breitling watches with a power reserve indication (a typical feature of the most refined watches, such as dress watches). It is not part of the most famous lines like the Chronomat or the Navitimer, but it is a niche model, highly appreciated for:

The quality of the movement (ETA 2892-A2 modified by Breitling to “Calibre 40”)

The aesthetic care (relatively thin case, golden details, clean design)

The balance between sport and class

The B14047 was sold as an elegant yet functional model, an everyday watch with a luxurious touch. It was less technical than a Navitimer or Emergency, but more refined than a Colt or a time-only model.
